      "content": "Ah, the elusive memory leak, a trickster in the world of embedded systems. It's like a mischievous goblin that hides in the shadows, always one step ahead of us. But fear not, for we have a few more tricks up our sleeve to catch this slippery creature.\n\nFirst, let's consider the possibility of memory fragmentation. In the realm of embedded systems, where memory is often as precious as a dragon's hoard, fragmentation can be a silent thief. It's like a goblin that eats through your memory, leaving behind a trail of unusable, fragmented chunks. To combat this, we can implement a memory pool or a fixed-size block allocator. This way, we can ensure that our memory is neatly organized, like a well-kept goblin village, making it easier to track and manage.\n\n```cpp\n#include <vector>\n\nclass MemoryPool {\npublic:\n    MemoryPool(size_t block_size, size_t num_blocks) : block_size_(block_size), num_blocks_(num_blocks) {\n        pool_.reserve(num_blocks_);\n        for (size_t i = 0; i < num_blocks_; ++i) {\n            pool_.push_back(new uint8_t[block_size_]);\n        }\n    }\n\n    ~",
